    base:desc "The Digital Twin’s communication stack is built on Mosquitto, the open‑source MQTT broker described in document 52, which implements the MQTT 3.1.1 protocol with explicit support for TLS encryption (currently TLS 1.2/1.3) and username/password authentication; optional client‑side certificates can be used for mutual TLS to guarantee that only authenticated controllers exchange telemetry.  At the application level, the platform employs Thingsboard (document 53) as an IoT back‑end, providing a multi‑tenant architecture with fine‑grained role‑based access control, JWT‑based device authentication, and mandatory TLS for all MQTT, HTTP and WebSocket traffic, with integrated audit logging for device, tenant and subscription events.  In the overall architecture, the RAMI 4.0 reference model (document 48) offers a dedicated cybersecurity layer that mandates risk assessment procedures, fail‑safe safeguards and a comprehensive resource‑based access control system, ensuring that safety‑critical data flows are isolated, encrypted, and monitored.  The Asset Administration Shell (document 50) encapsulates security metadata at the asset level—security categories, access rules, and cryptographic keys—allowing automated enforcement of ownership and authentication policies when the twin interfaces with the physical robot.  Finally, the functional mockup interface (FMI, document 51) can be employed to exchange simulation models in a version‑controlled, signed‑file format, further protecting model integrity and preventing unauthorized modification."
